SIMPLE: repulse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repulse
<hw>Re*pulse"</hw> <pr>(r?-p?ls")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Repulsed</conjf>
<pr>(-p?lst")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Repulsing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>repulsus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>repellere</ets>. See <er>Repel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
repel; to beat or drive back; <as>as, to <ex>repulse</ex> an assault; to
<ex>repulse</ex> the enemy.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Complete to have discovered and <qex>repulsed</qex>⟦br⟧
Whatever wiles of foe or seeming friend.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To repel by discourtesy, coldness, or denial; to
reject; to send away; <as>as, to <ex>repulse</ex> a suitor or a
proffer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repulse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Repulse
<hw>Re*pulse"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>repulsa</ets>, fr.
<ets>repellere</ets>, <ets>repulsum</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of repelling or driving back; also, the
state of being repelled or driven back.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By fate repelled, and with <qex>repulses</qex> tired.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He received in the <qex>repulse</qex> of Tarquin seven hurts in
the body.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Figuratively: Refusal; denial; rejection;
failure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repulseless</ent>⟦br⟧
